  "prompt": "What are de broghlie matter wave?",
  "response": "The de Broglie matter waves, named after the French physicist Louis de Broglie, refer to the wave-like behavior associated with particles of matter. De Broglie proposed in 1924 that just as light can exhibit both wave-like and particle-like properties, particles of matter, such as electrons, also have wave-like characteristics. This groundbreaking concept is a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics.\n\nThe wavelength associated with a particle, called the de Broglie wavelength, is given by the equation:\n\n\\[ \\lambda = \\frac{h}{p} \\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\( \\lambda \\) is the de Broglie wavelength,\n- \\( h \\) is Planck's constant (\\( h \\approx 6.626 \\times 10^{-34} \\) Js),\n- \\( p \\) is the momentum of the particle.\n\nMomentum \\( p \\) can be expressed as the product of the mass \\( m \\) of the particle and its velocity \\( v \\) (\\( p = mv \\)).\n\nThis principle implies that every moving particle (not only photons) has an associated wavelength, and thus can exhibit wave-like properties such as interference and diffraction. The matter wave concept was later experimentally confirmed, for instance, through electron diffraction experiments.\n\nIn summary, de Broglie matter waves describe the wave-particle duality of matter, which is one of the cornerstones of modern quantum theory.",
